(Beginner) Quest 4: Create EVM Subnet on Local Network
Introduction
In Quest 2, we learnt about Subnets and its features. For this quest, you will learn how to set up and deploy a Subnet on your local network using the Avalanche CLI (Command Line Interface) and interact with your Subnet using both Postman and cURL commands.
For queries on this quest, join our Discord, head to the #avalanche-helpdesk channel and look for this quest's post.
Learning Outcomes
By the end of this quest, you will be able to: 
  • Describe what Avalanche CLI is
  • Spin up and interact with a Subnet on your local network
  • Use Postman to issue API calls to interact with a Subnet on your local network
  • Use cURL commands to issue API calls to a Subnet on your local network
  • Describe the HyperSDK and its features
Deliverable
This quest has one deliverable.
  1. A screenshot of your cURL command and its output. Follow instructions in Step 14 for more details.

Quest Walkthrough
Step 1: Introduction to Avalanche CLI
Avalanche CLI is a command line tool that gives developers access to everything build-related on Avalanche - this includes setting up a local network, creating a Subnet, customizing the Subnet/VM configuration etc. Note that this tool is under rapid development, so it is advisable to check back on the documentation regularly for new updates.
Avalanche CLI Github - this Github repository contains information regarding Avalanche CLI functionalities and latest updates.
Step 2: (Gitpod) Setting Up Linux Cloud Instance
How to start
Unfortunately for Windows users, the Avalanche CLI can only be run on MacOS or on Linux distributions. To overcome this, we will use Gitpod to spin up a Linux cloud instance. If you are using a Mac or Linux machine and would like to install Avalanche CLI locally instead, skip this step and proceed to the next step!
Before we proceed to spin up our Linux cloud instance on Gitpod, well need to create a Github account. If you dont already have one, you can create your Github account here. 

Once you have your account, you can use this link to access your project through Gitpod, doing so will bring you to the page that looks like the image in How to start. Press on the Continue with Github button (as indicated in the image). Selecting that will open a separate page where it will ask for authorization for Gitpod to access your Github account.



After the authorization, there will be a popup from Gitpod asking you to select your code editor. Select the VS Code BROWSER option, as indicated in the image above. Gitpod will then prompt you for user authentication via sms. Follow the instructions provided.

After finishing the verification, a Visual Studios code editor will be opened in your web browser, similar to the image in Expected output below.

For Steps 3 to 6, youll be running the commands in your Gitpod terminal instead of a terminal on your local machine. This is because your local subnet (will be covered later) is hosted on the Linux cloud instance in Gitpod, and not on your local machine. 
Expected output
Step 3: Downloading and Installing the Avalanche CLI
Before we can create our Subnet, well first need to install the Avalanche CLI. Well be using a script to install Avalanche CLI. Open up a terminal and run the command below in it. This will download a script into the current directory that your terminal is in.
Note: if you are using Gitpod, youll need to run the commands below in your Gitpod terminal, not the terminal in your local machine.

curl https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ava-labs/avalanche-cli/main/scripts/install.sh --output install.sh

After you run the command, you should see an install.sh file in your directory. Run the command below to run the installation script.

sh install.sh

For learners that are using their local terminal - if your terminal gets stuck after running the command above, then feel free to revert to Step 2 and proceed using Gitpod instead.

Now well need to change the Avalanche CLI directory to match that of the Avalanche CLI commands. Run the two commands below separately in your terminal.

cd bin  export PATH=$PWD:$PATH

And were done installing Avalanche CLI!

Troubleshooting: If you dont see a bin folder after running sh install.sh, run this command export PATH=~/bin:$PATH instead. Note that even after you run this command, the bin folder will not appear, dont be alarmed. You can still proceed with the subsequent steps.
Step 4: Create an EVM Subnet on Your Local Network Using the Avalanche CLI
Now we can proceed to create and configure our first Subnet! We can do so by running the command below. Well be naming our Subnet - firstsubnet.
Note: if you are using using Gitpod, youll need to run the command below in your Gitpod terminal, not the terminal in your local machine.

avalanche subnet create firstsubnet

Once you execute this command, you will be prompted with several options; choose the following configuration: 
  • Choose a VM: SubnetEVM
  • Pick a chain ID: 1234
  • Token Symbol: Test
  • Subnet-EVM version: Use latest version
  • Set fees: Low disk user/ Low Throughput
  • Airdrop: Airdrop 1 million tokens to the default address (do not use in production)
  • Add a custom precompile to modify the EVM: No

And just like that, weve created our first Subnet! We can view a list of all the Subnets weve created with the command below. Try running it in your terminal, you should be able to see your Subnet in the output, similar to the image in Expected output. 

Note: for learners that are using Gitpod, youll need to run the command below in your Gitpod terminal, not the terminal in your local machine.

avalanche subnet list

As you can see, the configurations of the Subnet weve just created reflects the options we chose from earlier. If you look at the DEPLOYED section, youll see that this Subnet is not yet deployed to either the localhost nor the Avalanche Fuji Testnet. Before we can start interacting with the Subnet, well need to deploy it first. Well do so in the next step!

Troubleshooting: If you run into an error while running the command above, try the command below instead.

./avalanche subnet list
Expected output
Step 5: Deploying Your Subnet to the Local Network
Lets deploy our newly created Subnet to our local network. We can run the command below to do so.
Note: for learners that are using Gitpod, youll need to run the command below in your Gitpod terminal, not the terminal in your local machine.

avalanche subnet deploy firstsubnet

After doing so, select the Local Network option. Now sit back and wait! Your terminal should be printing out information on what it is currently processing. 

Once deployed, it will print out the configuration details in the terminal, as shown in the image in Expected output.

Troubleshooting: If you are using Gitpod and you face this error unexpected http status code: 403, try starting a new Gitpod session by opening an incognito window and repeating from Steps 2 again.

At this point, copy the RPC URL as it would be needed later on when were making our API calls. RPC stands for Remote Procedure Call - it is a set of communication protocols and interfaces that the client uses to interact with blockchain. 

By extension, an RPC URL is essentially the address of a node. Since well be interacting with our Subnet in the later steps, well need to take note of our Subnets RPC URL to be able to communicate with it.
Expected output
Step 6: Understanding Subnet Details
Now that weve deployed our Subnet, we can run the describe command below to view details of the configuration which we used to deploy our Subnet.
Note: for learners that are using Gitpod, youll need to run the command below in your Gitpod terminal, not the terminal in your local machine.

avalanche subnet describe firstsubnet

After running the command, you should get the following output displayed in your terminal. Lets find out what each section means!


In the Details section, general information of the Subnet and blockchain is displayed. Do note that the Subnet ID and blockchain ID are generated on deployment and thus the values you see in your terminal would not match what is in the image above.


In the Gas Config section, you can find information regarding how the gas fees are set up. As this was a pre-configured selection, your terminal output should look the same as what is displayed in the image above. 


The Airdrop section shows the account that has been given all of the initial tokens. If you recall, earlier on when we were creating the Subnet, we chose the option of airdropping all 1 million tokens to the default address, which is 0x8db97C7cEcE249c2b98bDC0226Cc4C2A57BF52FC.



The last portion is the Precompiles section. Since we didnt add any, it should state No precomplies set.

The describe command is just one of many commands you can use to interact with your Subnet. For more details on creating and deploying your Subnet, you can refer here.

Keep your terminal open as well be referring back to it for information in the subsequent steps!
Step 7: (Gitpod) Exposing Port
This step is only relevant for learners who are using Gitpod. If youre doing this quest locally on your machine, please skip this step and proceed to the next step. For learners who are using Gitpod, well need to do one additional step here before proceeding. Since were using a Linux cloud instance hosted on Gitpod, well need a way for our local machine to communicate with the cloud instance - well do this by exposing a port on Gitpod.
Remember the RPC URL you copied earlier? This is its format:
  • http://127.0.0.1:{port_number}/ext/bc/blockchain_ID/rpc

Take note of the port number, since this is the port well be exposing. Youll need to switch to the PORTS tab, which is beside the TERMINAL tab at the bottom of your Gitpod page. 

Once there, find the row with the port number identified earlier and right click on the port number. Then, select the Make Public option. After doing so, youll notice that the State has been changed to open (public). Refer to the image in Expected output if you require a reference.

Then, copy the address beside that port number. This will be the URL that well be using to interact with our Subnet in the next few steps. But before we do that, well need to construct our new RPC URL, the format should be as follows. The blockchain_ID can be taken from the old RPC URL.
  • {public_URL}/ext/bc/blockchain_ID/rpc

For example, if your original RPC URL was this:
  • http://127.0.0.1:9652/ext/bc/2HAtqoJ6qPzSVpuTNHrmH5pTsmSt4SvQLByrBTtHBL5noJDKx2/rpc
Your new RPC URL to use is:
  • https://9652-stackupdev-advancingint-vyd9ahq871m.ws-us77.gitpod.io/ext/bc/2HAtqoJ6qPzSVpuTNHrmH5pTsmSt4SvQLByrBTtHBL5noJDKx2/rpc

Now that we have our RPC URL, we can proceed with the next steps! Note that for all subsequent steps, whenever youre using an RPC URL, you should be using this new URL.
Expected output
Step 8: Using Postman to Get Chain ID of Subnet
In the next few steps, well be using Postman to issue API calls to interact with our newly deployed Subnet! If you havent downloaded Postman and imported the Avalanche collection, refer to Quest 3. Ensure that you only proceed with this quest after youve completed the above. This is because well be using the same imported collection and environment variables to interact with our new blockchain.
In this step, well be using Postman to call the Subnet blockchain RPC via the URL that we copied earlier.

This endpoint would allow us to query the RPC to check the chain ID of the Subnet which we set during the creation of the Subnet. The chain ID is the unique identifier that we assigned to the Subnet during creation. Note that the chain ID is different from the blockchain ID that is generated during the same process.



Open up Postman. In your Collections directory, navigate to the EVM folder then find the POST eth_chainId request and click on it. Then, replace the entire URL with your Subnets RPC URL, which can be taken from your terminal. Note that if you used Gitpod, the RPC URL should be the one generated in Step 7. Refer to the image above if you are unsure (if the image is too small, right click on it and press Open Image In New Tab).

Once the URL has been replaced, you can issue the API call and you should be returned with an output similar to the image in Expected output. Note that since the result is in hexadecimal format, you will need to convert it into decimals using a converter, such as this. If you convert 0x4d2 to decimal, you should get 1234, which is what we declared as the Chain ID while we were creating our Subnet!
Expected output
Step 9: Using Postman to Check Base Fee of Subnet
Now lets issue another API to our Subnet blockchain to check its base fee. To recap - the base fee is the minimum fee that will be charged for a transaction on a blockchain. 
Just like the previous step, youll need to navigate to the EVM folder. But this time, click on the POST eth_baseFee request instead. Then, replace the entire RPC URL and issue the API call.

This endpoint will allow us to query the base fee for each transaction for the Subnet that is determined by the pre-set configuration that we have chosen during the creation of the Subnet. 

After firing off the API call, you should be returned with an output similar to the image in Expected output. Once again, the value returned is in hexadecimal format. After converting it to decimal, you should get a value of 25000000000. 

If you open up your terminal now and scroll to the Gas Config section, youll see that the MinBaseFee tallies with the output from the API call as it also 25000000000. Nice!
Expected output
Step 10: cURL Commands
To recap, weve been using Postman as a convenient means to issue API calls to the blockchain. However, if you recall in Quest 3, we mentioned that it is also possible to issue API calls programmatically to the blockchain using cURL commands in the terminal. So lets try that out in the next few steps!
To recap, cURL, which stands for client URL, is a command line tool that developers use to transfer data to and from a server. Essentially, it lets you communicate with a server by specifying its location (in the form of a URL) and the data you want to send to it. Following which, the server will return a response accordingly.

There are 2 ways to obtain cURL commands to issue API calls to the blockchain. The first is to get it from the official Avalanche Documentation. The second is to utilise Postmans feature of converting requests to other programming languages. 

This is an example of how you can use this feature. Open up any one of the requests, on the right hand side of your screen, click on the code icon
, which is the third icon.



This will display a code snippet section where you can click the drop down menu - select cURL. This will produce a cURL command that you can use in your terminal (as shown in the image above).
Step 11: Using a cURL Command to Get Chain ID of Subnet
Now lets get our hands dirty with cURL commands! In Step 8, we used Postman to issue an API call to get the Chain Id of our Subnet. Lets try doing that but with a cURL command instead. 
Open up a local terminal in your machine (note that even for learners using Gitpod, you should be using a local terminal, NOT a Gitpod terminal). Replace replace_with_your_RPC_URL in the code below with your RPC URL and run the command in your terminal.

curl -X POST --data '{   "jsonrpc":"2.0",   "id"   :1,   "method" :"eth_chainId",   "params" :[] }' -H 'content-type:application/json;' {replace_with_your_RPC_URL}

Troubleshooting: If you see "error":{"code":-32700,"message":"parse error"} in your output after running the command, it is highly likely that there is some hidden formatting issues that were encountered whilst copying and pasting the command. To overcome this, open a text editor like Microsoft Word and paste the command in as Values only or Unformatted Text. Then after youre done replacing the RPC URL, copy the command from your text editor, paste it into your terminal and run it. 

After running that command, you should get the same result as you did in Step 8, i.e. {"jsonrpc":"2.0","id":1,"result":"0x4d2"}. Refer to the image in Expected output if you need a reference. Cool! We just fired off our first cURL command in our terminal to interact with our Subnet.
Expected output
Step 12: Using a cURL Command to Get Base Fee of Subnet
Same as the previous step, lets use a cURL command to achieve what we did in Step 9 when we used Postman to issue an API call to check the base fee of our Subnet. 
In your local terminal, copy the command below and paste it into your terminal. Remember to replace replace_with_your_RPC_URL with your RPC URL. Note that even if youre using Gitpod, you should be running the command below using a terminal on your local machine, not the terminal in Gitpod.

curl -X POST --data '{   "jsonrpc":"2.0",   "id"   :1,   "method" :"eth_baseFee",   "params" :[] }' -H 'content-type:application/json;' {replace_with_your_RPC_URL}

Troubleshooting: If you see "error":{"code":-32700,"message":"parse error"} in your output after running the command, it is highly likely that there is some hidden formatting issues that were encountered whilst copying and pasting the command. To overcome this, open a text editor like Microsoft Word and paste the command in as Values only or Unformatted Text. Then after youre done replacing the RPC URL, copy the command from your text editor, paste it into your terminal and run it. 

Similarly, you should get the same output as you did in Step 9. Refer to the image in Expected output for a reference.
Expected output
Step 13: Using a cURL Command to Get Account Balance
Now lets try making a different API call, one that we havent yet tried with Postman - issuing a cURL command to query an account balance. Remember during the Subnet creation, there was one account that was airdropped with all 1 million of the initial tokens? 
Now we will be querying that account balance to see if the tokens have indeed been correctly airdropped all 1 million of the initial tokens.

Copy the command below and paste it into a text editor. This time, youll need to replace 2 portions of the code - replace_with_the_airdrop_wallet_address and replace_with_your_RPC_URL. Well leave you to find out where to find the airdrop wallet address! Same as the previous 2 steps, even if youre using Gitpod, you should be running the command below using a terminal on your local machine, not the terminal in Gitpod.

curl -X POST --data '{                                                                              "jsonrpc":"2.0",   "id"   :1,   "method" :"eth_getBalance",   "params" :[
"replace_with_the_airdrop_wallet_address",
 "latest"
   ] }' -H 'content-type:application/json;' {replace_with_your_RPC_URL}

Troubleshooting: If you see "error":{"code":-32700,"message":"parse error"} in your output after running the command, it is highly likely that there is some hidden formatting issues that were encountered whilst copying and pasting the command. To overcome this, open a text editor like Microsoft Word and paste the command in as Values only or Unformatted Text. Then after youre done replacing the RPC URL, copy the command from your text editor, paste it into your terminal and run it.

Troubleshooting: If you see "error":{"code":-32602,"message":"invalid argument 0: json: cannot unmarshal hex string without 0x prefix into Go value of type common.Address"} in your output after running the command, check that there is no whitespace before your wallet address in the code.

Once you run your command, you should get an output that returns a hexadecimal value. Use the same converter we used in the earlier steps to do the conversion and youll see that the value matches the number of tokens airdropped to that wallet. Voila!

Step 15: (Optional Learning) Introduction to HyperSDK
HyperSDK is the first framework for building high performance virtual machines (VM) from scratch on Avalanche, providing developers a foundation to build the fastest blockchains in the world. As weve learnt in this quest as well as in Quest 2, creating a custom VM is one of the most powerful ways to build on Avalanche, and HyperSDK was precisely engineered to improve this process.
HyperSDK was designed to simplify and accelerate the development of custom VMs, making it safer and easier for developers to launch their own optimized blockchain. It achieves this by abstracting away common runtime complexities so that developers can focus on customizations that matter to them. With this lightning fast execution environment, the amount of coding required by developers is massively reduced, decreasing the time taken to build a blockchain runtime from multiple months to just a few days!

Blockchains built with HyperSDK are called HyperChains and can be adapted for any function the developer wishes. From NFT marketplaces to DeFi protocols, HyperSDK ushers in a new era for Avalanche builders to express their full creativity. A demo of the first HyperVM, IndexVM, can be found here.

Since theres quite a lot to cover regarding the HyperSDK, please feel free to refer here if you would like a more comprehensive overview of the HyperSDK. Or if you prefer Tweet threads, refer here for a Tweet thread written by Patrick OGrady, the Head of Engineering at Ava Labs! In it, he provides context for why the HyperSDK was created as well as highlights some of his favourite features of the HyperSDK.

Note: the HyperSDK is still considered ALPHA software and is not safe to use in production. The framework is under active development and may change significantly over the coming months as its modules are optimized and audited.
Step 16: (Optional Learning) HyperSDK Features
Now that we know a bit more about what the HyperSDK is and the value it brings, lets dive a bit deeper and explore what are some of its features that make it such a powerful piece of technology. Listed below are some of the features of the HyperSDK:
  • Efficient State Management - All HyperSDK state is stored using x/merkledb, a path-based merkelized radix tree implementation provided by avalanchego. This high-performance data structure minimizes the on-disk footprint of any hypervm out-of-the-box by deleting any data that is no longer part of the current state (without performing any costly reference counting)
  • Optimized Block Execution Out-of-the-Box - HyperSDK enables for fast and efficient block verification and state management by utilising state pre-fetching and parallel signature verification
  • Account Abstraction - Instead of relying on Actions, HyperSDK uses a registry of supported Auth modules that are used to validate each type of transaction
  • Nonce-less and Expiring Transactions - HyperSDK transactions do not use nonces to protect against replay attack like many other account-based blockchains. This means that users can submit transactions concurrently from a single account without worrying about ordering them properly or getting stuck on a transaction that was dropped by the mempool
  • Easy Functionality Upgrades - Convenient editing of features/configurations of a blockchain even after a blockchain has been deployed
  • Proposer-Aware Gossip - Unlike the VMs that live on the Avalanche Primary Network, the HyperSDK only gossips transactions to the next few preferred block proposers (using Snowman++'s lookahead logic), thus reducing the amount of unnecessary transaction gossip
  • Transaction Results and Execution Rollback - HyperSDK allows for any Action to return a result from execution (which can be any arbitrary bytes), the amount of fee units it consumed, and whether or not it was successful (if unsuccessful, all state changes are rolled back)
  • Support for Generic Storage Backends - Developers can explicitly specify which storage backends to use for each object type (state vs blocks vs metadata)
  • Unified Metrics, Tracing, and Logging - HyperSDK provides detailed metrics and comprehensive tracing to any hypervm out-of-the-box. These metrics and traces are aggregated by avalanchego and can be accessed using the /ext/metrics endpoint

As you can see from the long list of features above, the HyperSDK is definitely a powerful framework for building VMs on Avalanche. We highly encourage you to learn more about what the HyperSDK has to offer here.
